# TypeScript Mapped Types - Comprehensive Guide

Based on the provided CSS content from the TypeScript website, I cannot find specific information about mapped types in the CSS stylesheet provided. The content appears to be styling rules for the TypeScript documentation website rather than documentation about mapped types themselves.

However, I can provide you with the standard TypeScript mapped types information:

## Basic Syntax

Mapped types allow you to create new types by transforming properties of existing types:

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};
```

## Key Components

1. **`keyof T`** - Iterates over all property keys of type T
2. **`in`** - Maps over each key
3. **`T[K]`** - Accesses the property type

## Mapping Modifiers

### Adding/Removing Readonly

```typescript
// Add readonly
type Readonly<T> = {
  readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};

// Remove readonly
type Mutable<T> = {
  -readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};
```

### Adding/Removing Optional

```typescript
// Add optional
type Optional<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]?: T[K];
};

// Remove optional
type Required<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]-?: T[K];
};
```

## Key Remapping with `as`

```typescript
type Getters<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as `get${Capitalize<string & K>}`]: () => T[K];
};

interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

// Results in: { getName: () => string; getAge: () => number }
type PersonGetters = Getters<Person>;
```

## Practical Examples

```typescript
// Make all properties nullable
type Nullable<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null;
};

// Create a record of property names to their types
type PropertyTypes<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: T[K];
};

// Filter properties by type
type StringPropertiesOnly<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as T[K] extends string ? K : never]: T[K];
};
```

For complete documentation, visit the [TypeScript Handbook on Mapped Types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/mapped-types.html).

# TypeScript Classes - Comprehensive Guide

Based on the TypeScript documentation, here's a complete overview of TypeScript class features:

## Basic Class Structure

```typescript
class Point {
  x = 0;
  y = 0;
}

const pt = new Point();
pt.x = 0;
pt.y = 0;
```

## Constructors

```typescript
class Point {
  x: number;
  y: number;

  constructor(x = 0, y = 0) {
    this.x = x;
    this.y = y;
  }
}
```

## Parameter Properties

Automatically declare and initialize class members from constructor parameters:

```typescript
class Point {
  constructor(public x = 0, public y = 0) {}
}

// Equivalent to:
class Point {
  public x = 0;
  public y = 0;
  constructor(x = 0, y = 0) {
    this.x = x;
    this.y = y;
  }
}
```

## Access Modifiers

```typescript
class Greeter {
  public greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }

  protected getName() {
    return "world";
  }

  private getSecret() {
    return "secret";
  }
}
```

### Visibility Levels:
- **`public`** (default): accessible everywhere
- **`protected`**: accessible within class and subclasses
- **`private`**: accessible only within the class

## ECMAScript Private Fields

```typescript
class Dog {
  #barkAmount = 0;

  bark() {
    this.#barkAmount++;
  }

  static properties() {
    // Private fields are always private
  }
}

// Cannot access from outside:
// dog.#barkAmount; // ❌ Error
```

**Differences from `private`:**
- Private fields use `#` prefix (hard private at runtime)
- `private` keyword is TypeScript-only (erased after compilation)
- Private fields are always private; `private` can be overridden by access modifiers

## Getters and Setters

```typescript
class Thing {
  _size = 0;

  get size(): number {
    return this._size;
  }

  set size(value: string | number | boolean) {
    let num = Number(value);
    if (!Number.isFinite(num)) {
      this._size = 0;
      return;
    }
    this._size = num;
  }
}
```

## Static Members

```typescript
class MyClass {
  static x = 0;

  static printX() {
    console.log(MyClass.x);
  }
}

console.log(MyClass.x);
MyClass.printX();
```

### Static Blocks

```typescript
class Foo {
  static #count = 0;

  static {
    try {
      const lastInstances = loadLastInstances();
      Foo.#count += lastInstances.length;
    } catch (e) {
      // ...
    }
  }
}
```

## Abstract Classes

```typescript
abstract class Base {
  abstract getName(): string;

  printName() {
    console.log("Hello, " + this.getName());
  }
}

class Derived extends Base {
  getName() {
    return "world";
  }
}
```

## Implements

```typescript
interface Pingable {
  ping(): void;
}

class Sonar implements Pingable {
  ping() {
    console.log("ping!");
  }
}

class Ball implements Pingable {
  // ❌ Error: missing ping()
}
```

## Class Expressions

```typescript
const someClass = class <T> {
  content: T;
  constructor(value: T) {
    this.content = value;
  }
};

const m = new someClass("Hello"); // m: someClass
```

## `this` Types

```typescript
class Box {
  contents: string = "";

  set(value: string): this {
    this.contents = value;
    return this;
  }
}

class ClearableBox extends Box {
  clear() {
    this.contents = "";
  }
}

const b = new ClearableBox();
b.set("world").clear(); // ✅ Works with subclass
```

## Type-Only Field Declarations

```typescript
class C {
  foo: number = 0;
  declare bar: number; // No runtime representation
}
```

## Mixins Pattern

```typescript
type Constructor<T = {}> = new (...args: any[]) => T;

function scale<T extends Constructor>(Base: T) {
  return class extends Base {
    scale(factor: number) {
      // Use this.x, this.y from Base
    }
  };
}

class Shape {
  x = 0;
  y = 0;
}

const ScaledShape = scale(Shape);
const shape = new ScaledShape();
shape.scale(2);
```

## Structural Compatibility

```typescript
class Point {
  x: number = 0;
  y: number = 0;
}

class Point3D {
  x: number = 0;
  y: number = 0;
  z: number = 0;
}

const p: Point = new Point3D(); // ✅ Structurally compatible
```

## Key Differences: `private` vs `#`

| Feature | `private` | `#` |
|---------|-----------|-----|
| Scope | TypeScript only | JavaScript runtime |
| Override | Can be bypassed | Always private |
| Access pattern | `this.prop` | `this.#prop` |
| Inheritance | Inheritable | Always private |

This comprehensive guide covers all major TypeScript class features for robust object-oriented programming.

# Template Literal Types in TypeScript

I've reviewed the provided CSS content, which appears to be styling for the TypeScript documentation website. Unfortunately, this CSS file does not contain information about template literal types—it only contains style definitions for the site's layout, navigation, and UI components.

To provide you with accurate information about TypeScript's template literal types, I would need access to the actual TypeScript documentation or handbook content (typically in HTML or markdown format), not the CSS styling.

## What I Can Tell You

Based on TypeScript's official documentation, template literal types include:

### Basic Syntax
```typescript
type Greeting = `Hello, ${string}`;
```

### Union Distribution
```typescript
type EmailLocaleIDs = "welcome_email" | "email_heading";
type FooterLocaleIDs = "footer_label" | "footer_copyright";
type AllLocaleIDs = `${EmailLocaleIDs | FooterLocaleIDs}_id`;
// Result: "welcome_email_id" | "email_heading_id" | "footer_label_id" | "footer_copyright_id"
```

### Intrinsic String Manipulation Types
- **`Capitalize<StringType>`** - Capitalizes the first character
- **`Uncapitalize<StringType>`** - Uncapitalized the first character
- **`Uppercase<StringType>`** - Converts all characters to uppercase
- **`Lowercase<StringType>`** - Converts all characters to lowercase

### Practical Example
```typescript
type Cases<T extends string> = {
  uppercase: Uppercase<T>;
  lowercase: Lowercase<T>;
  capitalize: Capitalize<T>;
  uncapitalize: Uncapitalize<T>;
};
```

